      "symbolism": "Myrtle's evergreen nature represents immortal and eternal love that never fades. The white flowers symbolize beauty, purity, and divine grace. The dark berries represent fertility and the fruits of love. The plant's sweet fragrance embodies the intoxicating nature of romantic love and desire. Growing from the place where Aphrodite first touched the earth, myrtle serves as a living connection between the divine and mortal realms of love. Its use in both weddings and funerals represents love's power to transcend death.",
      "culturalSignificance": "Myrtle permeated Greek culture as the ultimate symbol of love and marriage. Wedding ceremonies were unthinkable without myrtle crowns. Athenian magistrates wore myrtle wreaths as symbols of civic authority and virtue. The plant was so associated with Aphrodite that depictions of the goddess regularly included myrtle branches or wreaths. Myrtle oil was prized in perfumery and cosmetics. The tradition of using myrtle in weddings continued into Roman times and influenced later European wedding customs. Place names like Myrtea and personal names like Myrrhinƒì (Myrrhine) derived from the plant."
